wireguard-go-bridge

Python FFI bindings for wireguard-go. PersistentDevice with automatic
IPC state persistence and key generation.


v2.1.2 - 2026-03-24
-------------------

  Maintenance release covering publish infrastructure, log hygiene,
  and the first written documentation for the bridge.

  * Vendor artifact hosting moved from Cloudflare Pages
    (vendor-artifacts.phantom.tc, served from the dev/vendor branch)
    to R2 direct upload, after the Pages setup ran into its service
    limits.
  * Publish workflow switched to dispatch-only (no automatic publish
    on push).
  * Suppressed "no known endpoint" log noise emitted by peers that
    have not yet established connectivity.
  * Publish workflow handles idempotent vendor pushes — re-running
    the same version no longer fails the job.
  * Added README and Turkish README with architecture diagrams.
  * __version__ bumped to 2.1.2.


v2.1.0 - 2026-03-02
-------------------

  The actual thinning. Breaking change relative to v2.0.

  v2.0 had replaced the v1 concept-per-file layout with a
  centralized state machine plus an SQLite persistence layer on
  the Go side — more ambitious, not less. v2.1 throws that out.
  Roughly 6,000 lines of Go are deleted (bridge/, db/, multihop/
  packages gone) and all high-level logic moves to Python:
  state, DB management, client wallet. The Go side is reduced to
  PersistentDevice — a long-lived handle that wraps wireguard-go
  and auto-persists on every IpcSet — plus key generation and
  utility entry points. Nothing else.

  * PersistentDevice introduced on the Go side: owns the tunnel
    handle across calls, auto-persists state to an SQLite file on
    every IpcSet, restores from DB on startup.
  * FFI exports rewritten down to PersistentDevice + Key + a small
    set of utility entry points. filterIpcDump strips five
    read-only fields so the dump is safely round-trippable.
  * bridge/, db/, and multihop/ packages removed from the Go side
    (~6,092 lines deleted).
  * Python layer filled out: WireGuardBridge class (typed,
    __slots__, context manager), keys module (generate private
    key, derive public key, hex ↔ base64), native BridgeError
    exception hierarchy.
  * Test infrastructure rebuilt. netns-test/ retired in favour of
    a 3-container Docker topology — bridge, exit-server, client —
    driven by a parameterless test_runner.py that builds images
    and syncs code automatically. 52 tests (51 unit + 1
    integration) at 99% coverage; the integration test walks
    tunnel-up, crash recovery, and client multihop in three
    phases.
  * _ffi library discovery fixed to look beside the package
    instead of in dist/ (matters once installed as a wheel).


v2.0.0 - 2026-03-01
-------------------

  Bridge-db rewrite. Breaking change. Short-lived.

  v1.0 split the Go surface across one file per WireGuard concept
  — allowed IPs, cookies, crypto, device, keys, logger, misc,
  peer, UAPI. That concept-per-file layout was collapsed here
  into a centralized design: a single state machine
  (bridge/state.go, ~1k lines, Status lifecycle from
  Uninitialized → NeedsSetup → Ready → Running → Error), an
  SQLite persistence layer (db/ — client, server, multihop,
  stats, schema), and a multihop config package.

  The intent was to give the bridge a coherent state model
  instead of a pile of wrappers. In practice it just moved the
  weight around: the bridge still owned too much of the product's
  semantics, and keeping it aligned with upstream wireguard-go
  was no easier than before. v2.1 retires most of this layer one
  day later.

  * Centralized bridge state machine replaces the v1 per-concept
    files.
  * SQLite-backed persistence layer added (client, server,
    multihop, stats, schema).
  * Multihop configuration added as a first-class concern.
  * Publish workflow split into separate test, build, and publish
    stages (previously one monolithic job).
  * Publish target moved to dev/vendor as a flat directory with a
    VERSION file, replacing GitHub Release artifact hosting.
  * Removed auto-generated release notes from the publish step.


v1.0.0 - 2026-02-28
-------------------

  Initial release. Reorganized in v2.0 and again in v2.1;
  documented here for historical continuity.

  First cut of the native FFI bridge for wireguard-go. The Go
  surface was split by WireGuard concept — one file per concern
  (allowed IPs, cookies, crypto, device, keys, logger,
  miscellaneous, peer, UAPI) — and the Python side called into
  those directly.

  * Native FFI bridge with Python bindings over a concept-per-
    file Go layout.
  * UAPI/Run FFI surface with netns-based integration tests
    (retired in v2.1 for the Docker topology).
  * Package release workflow with build artifacts published to a
    separate development branch (kept the source branch clean).
  * THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES inventory.
